<steps>
<step><cmd>Select the <uicontrol>MVS Files</uicontrol> subsystem of
a remote system connection.</cmd></step>
<step><cmd>Right-click and select <menucascade><uicontrol>Menu</uicontrol>
<uicontrol>Allocate VSAM Data Set</uicontrol></menucascade>.</cmd><info><note>You
can also press Ctrl+4 to allocate a new VSAM data set.</note></info>
</step>
<step><cmd>On the first page of the wizard:</cmd>
<substeps>
<substep><cmd>Accept the name that is provided in the <uicontrol>Connection
Name</uicontrol> field.</cmd></substep>
<substep><cmd>Select or type the high-level qualifier for the data
set from the list.</cmd></substep>
<substep><cmd>In the <uicontrol>Data Set Name</uicontrol> field, specify
the name that follows the combination of high-level qualifier and
period. </cmd><stepxmp>For example, if the high-level qualifier is <filepath>MYFILES</filepath> and
if you want to allocate the data set <filepath>MYFILES.TEST.VSAM</filepath>,
type the string <userinput>TEST.VSAM</userinput> in the <uicontrol>Data
Set Name</uicontrol> field.</stepxmp></substep>
<substep><cmd>Click <uicontrol>Next</uicontrol>.</cmd></substep>
</substeps>
</step>
<step><cmd>On page 2, click <uicontrol>Specify characteristics (Advanced
allocation)</uicontrol> and then click <uicontrol>Next</uicontrol> to
specify allocation values such as VSAM file type, associations, and
cluster attributes.</cmd></step>
<step><cmd>Specify the allocation values. </cmd><info>For field-level
help, see the related links. For details on what values are required
for different uses, contact your <tm tmtype="reg" trademark="z/OS">z/OS</tm> system
administrator. </info></step>
<step><cmd>To allocate the data set, click <uicontrol>Finish</uicontrol>.</cmd>
</step>
</steps>
</taskbody>
